description.p:
preparing a zirconium sol, mixed with a thickening agent and optionally with the element or elements selected;


adding, only when microspheres are to be obtained, a non-ionic surface-active agent (for example iso-octylphenoxy-polyethoxy-ethanol), to the sol;


dripping, obtaining spheres, or atomizing, obtaining microspheres, the sol into a basic gelation bath;


aging the spheres or microspheres of gel thus obtained;


washing the spheres or microspheres with water up to pH=9 and draining them without drying them;


impregnating the spheres or microspheres of gel with an aqueous solution of ammonium sulfate or, if it is not possible to obtain cogelation of the element selected with the zirconium hydroxide, with a solution of ammonium sulfate and a salt of said element selected;


drying the spheres or microspheres and calcinating them in air at temperatures ranging from 450 (degree)  C. to 700 (degree)  C.

The process for the isomerization of aliphatic hydrocarbons with a low molecular weight, a further object of the present invention, by means of the solid superacid catalysts specified above containing aluminum, comprises the following steps:


introducing the calcined spheres into a reactor and activating them in air at a temperature ranging from 300 (degree)  C. to 500 (degree)  C., preferably from 450 (degree)  C. to 500 (degree)  C.;


introducing a reagent mixture with an H2 /n-paraffin ratio varying from 2/1 to 10/1, preferably from 3/1 to 5/1, with a space velocity (GHSV) ranging from 2000 to 10000 h-1 ;


effecting the reaction at temperatures lower than 300 (degree)  C., preferably from 230 to 270 (degree)  C.

From a structural point of view, for the various materials calcined under the same temperature conditions and for the same time (3 hours), the X-diffraction shows:


for products calcined at 450 (degree)  C.: amorphous materials, for all sulfate contents and for Al2 O3  >= 2.5%; materials slightly crystallized, for the two lowest contents of SO42- and Al2 O3 =1.66%, amorphous for higher sulfate contents; a well crystallized material for the lower sulfate content for Al2 O3 =0.83%, a slightly crystallized material for SO42- =2.8% (with respect to the dry product) and amorphous materials in the other cases;


for products calcined at 550 (degree)  C.: amorphous materials, for the two higher sulfate contents and for Al2 O3  >= 4.2%, materials slightly crystallized for the other contents of SO42- ; an amorphous material for the higher sulfate content and for Al2 O3 =2.5%, slightly crystallized for SO42- =7.6% (with respect to the dry product) and materials becoming increasingly more crystallized on reducing the sulfate content; materials slightly crystallized for the higher sulfate content and Al2 O3  <= 1.66% and becoming increasingly more crystallized on reducing the sulfate content;


for products calcined at 650 (degree)  C.: well crystallized materials for all sulfate contents and for Al2 O3  >= 1.66%; particularly well crystallized materials for Al2 O3 =0.83% and for all sulfate contents.

The "crush strength" measurements, only effected on alternating sulfate contents and for calcination temperatures of 550 (degree)  C. and 650 (degree)  C. (the latter being more interesting for the isomerization tests), showed the following tendency:


for products calcined at 550 (degree)  C.: excellent mechanical characteristics, in the order of 37-38 N;


for products calcined at 650 (degree)  C.: much lower mechanical resistances, of about 11-12 N, but in any case capable of keeping the material structurally integral, even after use.
